            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is a perpetuity?</h2>
              <p>
                In finance, a <strong>perpetuity</strong> is a stream of equal
                cash flows that continues forever, with no fixed end date. It is
                a useful idealization for valuing assets that are expected to
                generate stable cash flows for a very long time.
              </p>
              <p>Common examples include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Certain types of <strong>preferred stock</strong> that pay a
                  fixed dividend indefinitely.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Theoretical <strong>consol bonds</strong> that never mature.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Real estate or businesses modeled as having
                  <strong>stable cash flows</strong> far into the future.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Perpetuity formulas</h2>

              <h3>1. Level perpetuity (no growth)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Present value of a level perpetuity:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ PV = \frac{C}{r} $$</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(PV\) = present value today</li>
                  <li>\(C\) = constant cash flow per period</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = discount rate per period (in decimal form)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>Rearranging the formula lets you solve for other variables:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Payment given PV and r:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ C = PV \times r $$</p>
                <p><strong>Discount rate given PV and C:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ r = \frac{C}{PV} $$</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Growing perpetuity</h3>
              <p>
                A <strong>growing perpetuity</strong> assumes the cash flow
                grows at a constant rate \(g\) each period. The standard formula
                uses the <em>next period</em> cash flow \(C_1\).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Present value of a growing perpetuity:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ PV = \frac{C_1}{r - g} \quad \text{with } r &gt; g $$</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(C_1\) = cash flow in the next period</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = discount rate per period</li>
                  <li>\(g\) = growth rate per period</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>Rearranged forms:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Next period cash flow given PV, r, g:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ C_1 = PV \times (r - g) $$</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Discount rate given PV, C<sub>1</sub>, g:</strong>
                </p>
                <p>$$ r = \frac{C_1}{PV} + g $$</p>
                <p><strong>Growth rate given PV, C<sub>1</sub>, r:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ g = r - \frac{C_1}{PV} $$</p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use the perpetuity calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select the perpetuity type.</strong>
                  Choose <em>Level perpetuity</em> for constant cash flows, or
                  <em>Growing perpetuity</em> if cash flows are expected to grow
                  at a constant rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose what to solve for.</strong>
                  You can compute the present value, the payment, the discount
                  rate, or (for growing perpetuities) the growth rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the known values.</strong>
                  Make sure the discount rate and growth rate are expressed per
                  the same period as the cash flows (e.g. annual, monthly).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate”.</strong>
                  The tool shows the result and a short explanation of the
                  formula used.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Level perpetuity (preferred stock)</h3>
              <p>
                A preferred share pays a fixed dividend of $5 per year, forever.
                Investors require a 6% annual return. What is the fair price of
                the share?
              </p>
              <p>Using the level perpetuity formula:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>$$ PV = \frac{C}{r} = \frac{5}{0.06} \approx 83.33 $$</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The fair value of the preferred share is about
                <strong>$83.33</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Growing perpetuity (Gordon Growth Model)</h3>
              <p>
                A company is expected to pay a dividend of $2 next year, and
                dividends are expected to grow at 3% per year forever. If
                investors require an 8% return, what is the stock price?
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  $$ PV = \frac{C_1}{r - g} = \frac{2}{0.08 - 0.03} =
                  \frac{2}{0.05} = 40 $$
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>The stock is worth <strong>$40</strong> under this model.</p>

              <h2>Perpetuity vs. annuity</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Annuity:</strong> fixed cash flows for a finite number
                  of periods (e.g. 20‑year bond).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Perpetuity:</strong> fixed (or steadily growing) cash
                  flows that continue forever.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In practice, no cash flow truly lasts forever, but the
                perpetuity model is a powerful approximation when the horizon is
                very long and later cash flows contribute little to present
                value due to discounting.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The discount rate and growth rate are assumed to be constant
                  over time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For growing perpetuities, the condition \(r &gt; g\) must
                  hold.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cash flows are assumed to arrive at regular intervals (e.g.
                  annually, monthly).
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Perpetuity FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is a perpetuity realistic in the real world?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Strictly speaking, no cash flow lasts forever. Perpetuities
                    are an idealized model that becomes very accurate when the
                    time horizon is long and the discount rate is positive,
                    because distant cash flows contribute very little to present
                    value. They are widely used in valuation, especially for
                    terminal value estimates.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What happens if the growth rate is higher than the discount
                    rate?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    If \(g \ge r\), the growing perpetuity formula breaks down:
                    the present value would be infinite or undefined. In that
                    case, the model is not appropriate and you should revisit
                    your assumptions about growth and required return.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this calculator for monthly or quarterly payments?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. Just ensure that the discount rate and growth rate (if
                    any) are expressed per the same period as the payments. For
                    example, for monthly payments, use a monthly discount rate
                    (annual rate divided by 12 as an approximation, or an exact
                    conversion if needed).
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How is perpetuity used in discounted cash flow (DCF) models?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    In DCF valuation, analysts often project detailed cash flows
                    for a finite number of years, then assume the business grows
                    at a stable rate thereafter. The value of all cash flows
                    beyond the forecast horizon is captured using a growing
                    perpetuity formula, known as the terminal value.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
